english:
  title: 'In Praise of the Eight Steeds: With Preface'
  author: Lee Gyejeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly observe that whenever an empire rises through the ages, it is always built upon the accumulated virtue of preceding sages who lay its foundation, and later sages who expand its base. Those who inherit the throne must celebrate and chronicle the deeds of their ancestors through song and verse, creating enduring principles for countless generations to uphold. The Zhou dynasty, founded when Houji received his fief, flourished for over a thousand years until the era of King Tai and King Ji, whose accumulated virtue reached its zenith. When Kings Wen and Wu received the Mandate of Heaven, and Kings Cheng and Zhou Gong carried on their legacy with eloquent embellishment, they composed hymns celebrating these virtues. The poems of "Great Brightness," "The Gourds," "August Heaven," and "The Life-giving People" rival the sun and stars in their radiance and endure forever like heaven and earth itself. Surely this is no mere chance! Respectfully, I reflect upon our own dynasty. From our earliest ancestors onwards, virtue has been transmitted through successive generations until Mojo established our foundation in the northern lands. His successors Yijo and Dojo inherited and cultivated this virtue, expanding what had been built before. By the time of Hwanjo, benevolence and trust spread far and wide, and adherents multiplied daily. Thus Heaven grew weary of the declining Goryeo and opened the Mandate to us. Our Great Ancestor possessed courage and wisdom unmatched in all history. He took upon himself the mission of saving the world and bringing peace to the people, campaigning north and south without rest or respite. Heroes rallied to his cause—some offering counsel in the war tent, others pledging their lives in service. And there were eight divine steeds as well, creatures of providence who charged forth in battle, galloping across the plains with such speed and power that nothing could withstand them. With hearts united with their riders, they achieved extraordinary deeds, true omens of a blessed age. By virtue of such supreme excellence, both heaven and all people turned their hearts toward him. Even the beasts of the realm responded to destiny, extending their swift legs to establish our kingdom's eternal, boundless reign. The great wisdom of Taejo surpassed all others; his decisive strategies conquered all difficulties and greatly magnified the nation's fortune. Our Lord, inheriting his vision and continuing his work, has brought peace and civilization through cultured governance. Remembering how arduous was the founding of earlier kings and how difficult the preservation of their legacy for posterity, he has gathered the extraordinary and displayed the magnificent, enshrining it in music. Nor has he forgotten even the humble service of beasts—he commanded artists to paint their forms and literati to compose tributes to their virtue. Thus does he honor the glorious deeds of his ancestors and impart enduring lessons to his heirs, sparing no effort in this sacred task. O, how sublime! Compared to the Zhou dynasty's receipt of Heaven's Mandate, it aligns as perfectly as a seal upon its impression. Truly, as the ancients and moderns say, the Way of the sage remains ever the same.

    In the autumn of the Year of the Rabbit, an examination was held for the literati. The Left Prime Minister Ha Yeon, Minister of Personnel Jeong In-ji, Minister of Rites Heo Hyu, and Chief of Staff Lee Sa-chol were appointed to oversee the selection. I myself had the honor of being included among them. The examination topic was set as "The Eight Steeds," a formal composition. The Prime Minister's poem of four lines was submitted first, and then all the literati were commanded to compose their own. Though my station keeps me near the throne, I dared not excuse myself from this task despite my humble talents. I therefore bow deeply and respectfully offer this praise:

    Heaven cherishes the people and selects the virtuous as their ruler.
    When sages arise, all creatures manifest themselves.
    When good fortune opens, auspicious omens precede it endlessly.
    The Shang sang of the dark bird; the Zhou sang of gourds and melons.
    These were enshrined in music and echo through the ages as one eternal day.

    Our dynasty alone has inherited humaneness and kindness through generations.
    We established our realm in the northern lands, laboring even in the potter's earthen pit.
    O, how great was our Great Ancestor! Courage and wisdom were Heaven's gifts to him.
    Moving with pity for people suffering in chaos, he swept north and south in conquest.
    As clouds bring forth dragons and wind brings forth tigers, so heroes gathered at his call.
    Some offered strategic counsel; some displayed their martial prowess.
    And the eight divine steeds were there, their swift hooves racing forth,
    Charging through perilous terrain and dangerous heights,
    Crushing the strong and breaking through enemy lines.
    With manes like wind-tossed hair and forelock like mist,
    With dragon-like patterns upon their flanks and tiger-like strength along their spines,
    They were the genuine creatures of ancient paintings, the singular portents of a blessed age.

    The succeeding ruler, inheriting the vision of his predecessor, has carried forward the glorious deeds.
    In celebrating these magnificent accomplishments, his thoughts even extend to the beasts.
    The painters have rendered their forms; the scribes have inscribed their words.
    These brilliant traces now shine forth to all generations without end—
    O, that through ten thousand years hence, great deeds shall remain forever adorned!
  footnotes:
    - The Eight Steeds refers to eight legendary horses that served the dynasty—here representing both literal steeds and symbolic emblems of the dynasty's providential mission.
    - The Zhou dynasty poems mentioned—"Great Brightness" (大明), "The Gourds" (綿瓜), "August Heaven" (皇矣), and "The Life-giving People" (生民)—are actual poems from the Book of Songs celebrating the Zhou's founding.
    - The comparison to the Zhou dynasty's receipt of the Mandate of Heaven reflects the Korean court's understanding of Joseon as the legitimate successor to heaven's favor, replacing the declining Goryeo.
    - The examination setting reflects a historical practice where the Korean court would commission literary works to commemorate significant achievements and moral lessons for posterity.
